snippet.textDisplay:
Once upon a time I thought I was strong, invincible. At 18 I could party all night, come home at 5.30, shower and go to work. Of my entire youth I don't remember rejecting an opportunity to see a band, go out for a drink, try to meet girls etc, because I was too tired.


Then, sometime when I wasn't watching time crept up on me. My energy slipped away. I found myself really suffering if I had a late night. A bad cold could flatten me. Last year the flu developed into pneumonia and I nearly died.


I am the same person that used to party all night. Am I worth less now?
When I look back over my life I have not cured cancer or developed a better mousetrap. The chances are that most of us won't.


I have had the time for serious inner examination. One thing I have learned is that every life is worthy, is meaningful no matter that person's age or station in life.
The homeless woman on skid-row is just as valuable as a Rockefeller. A month after they are dead they even look the same.


Novelist Pearl Buck once wrote; “Our society must make it right and possible for old people not to fear the young or be deserted by them, for the test of a civilization is the way that it cares for its helpless members.”
